2. Experimental procedure   Synthesis of Imi -cage . The mixture of TFTPP (300 mg, 0.86 mmol), (1S, 2S)-(+)-1,2-cyclohexanediamine (148.3 mg, 1.30 mmol) and MgSO 4 (834.0 mg, 6.93 mmol) in CHCl 3 (17 mL) was stirred at room temperature  for 48 h under nitrogen atmosphere. Then the organic liquid was collected by low -pressure filtration. The solvent was remo ved under vacuum to give the crude product, which was then dissolved in 1 mL of CHCl 3. A white precipitate was obtained upon addition of MeOH. The resulting solid was collected by centrifugation, and dried at 35 ¡«C under vacuum overnight to yield white tar get product S3   (361 mg , 90%): 1H NMR (600 MHz, CDC l3) Ñ´ (ppm) 7.67 (s, 6H), 7.31(d, J = 7.51 Hz, 12H), 6.99 (t, J = 7.49 Hz, 12H), 3.19 (d, J = 9.75 Hz, 6H), 2.13 (d, J = 12.00 Hz, 6H), 1.92 (M, 12H), 1.51 (M, 6H).
Synthesis of Phos -cage . Add TFTPP ( 300 mg, 0.86 mmol) and (1S, 2S) -(+)-1,2-cyclohexanediamine  (148.3  mg, 1.30 mmol) in to CHCl 3 (17 mL) under nitrogen atmosphere.

MeOH ( 17 mL) and NaBH 4 (1.31 g, 34.65  mmol) were added into the reaction mixture  after stirring at room temperature (r.t.) for 48 h. Then the mixture was stirred at r.t. for another 12 h. Subsequently,  H2O (50 mL) was added and the resulting mixture was extracted with CH 2Cl2 (20 mL, 3 times). The combined organic extracts were washed with water ( 30 mL) and saturated brine ( 30 mL) successively, dried over anhydrous Na 2SO 4. The volatiles were removed under vacuum to give the crude product. The residue was purified by flash column chromatography using CH 2Cl2-MeOH as the eluent to afford t he product as a white solid ( 386 m g, 97 %): 1H NMR (600 MHz, DMSO) Ñ´  (ppm)  7.26 (d, J = 7.66 Hz, 12H), 7.16 (t, J = 7.79 Hz, 12H), 3.66 (d, J = 14.09 Hz, 6H), 3,53 (d, J = 14.12 Hz, 6H), 2.39 (s, 6H), 2.20 (d, J = 8.76 Hz, 6H), 2.01 (d, J = 11.91 Hz, 6H), 1.64 (d, J = 7.12 Hz, 6H), 1.15 (t, J = 9.57 Hz, 6H) .

Synthesis of Semicage . The mixture of TFTPP (300 mg, 0.86 mmol) , cyclohexylamine (515.4 mg, 5.19 mmol) and MgSO 4 (834.0 mg, 6.93 mmol) in CHCl 3 (17 mL)  was stirred at r.t. for 48 h  under nitrogen atmosphere . Then  the organic liquid was collected by low -pressure filtration . The solvent was removed  under vacuum  to give the crude product, S4   which  was then dissolved in ~ 1 mL of CHCl 3. A white precipitate was then obtained upon addition o f MeOH.  The resulting solid  was isolated through centrifugation, washed with MeOH and n-hexnane three times, and then dried at 35 ¡«C under vacuum overnight to yield white target product  (449 mg, 88%): 1H NMR  (600 MHz, CDC l3) Ñ´ (ppm)  8.30 (s, 3H), 7.68(d, J = 7. 60 Hz, 6H), 7.32 (t, J = 7.70 Hz, 6H), 3.19 (M, 3H), 1.83 (d, J = 13.08  Hz, 6H), 1.73 (d, J = 10.71  Hz, 6H), 1.61 (d, J = 12. 58 Hz, 3H), 1.57 (t, J = 1 3.01 Hz, 6H), 1.37 (t, J = 12. 68 Hz, 6H). 13C NMR (600 MHz, CDC l3) Ñ´ (ppm) 157.05 , 136.14, 132.78 , 127.08 , 69.01 , 33.37 , 24.53 , 23.88 ; 31P NMR  (600 MHz, CDC l3) Ñ´ (ppm)  -5.4. ESI-MS: m/z for C39H48N3P, [M+H]+ 590.3658 (calcd 590.3659).

Synthesis of N -[8+12] -cage . The experimental procedure was followed a reported manuscript.2 To a round bottom flask was added (1S, 2S) -(+)-1,2-cyclohexanediamine (54 mg, 0.455 mmol) and CHC l3 (180 mL) under nitrogen atmosphere, a solution of tri(4 -formylphenyl)amine  (100 mg, 0.303 mmol) in  CHC l3 (90 mL) was added  slowly. The resulting mixture was heated  to reflux for 48 h. After completion of the reaction, solvent was removed . The obtained pale -yellow solid was washed with M eOH (5 ¨G 3 mL), and afforded as pure imine -based product  in an 80% yield (108 mg). T hen, the obtained solid was dissolved in the mixed solution of CHCl 3/MeOH=1/5 ( by volume)  under nitrogen atmosphere, NaBH 4 (115 mg,  3.03 mmol) was subsequently added slowly, stirred for another 12 hours at room temperature  The combined organic extracts were  then washed with water and saturated brine, dried over anhydrous Na 2SO 4, filtered and concentrated by vacuum. The N-[8+12] -cage was afforded as  yellow powder (110 mg, 87%). 1H NMR (600 MHz, CDC l3) Ñ´ (ppm)  7.14 (broad, m, 48H) , 6.86  (broad, m, 48H) , 3.85 (broad, m, 24H) , 3.63 (broad, m, 24H) , 2.18 -2.47 (broad, m, 48H) , 1.74 (broad, m, 24H), 1.25 (broad, m, 72H) .

S5   Culti vation of Single Crystal of Phos -cage . 500 mg Phos -cage  purified by flash chromatography column was added to a 100 ml round -bottomed flask, subsequently a mixture of CH 2Cl2 and EtOH (5/1, by volume) was added to dissolve it completely. After standing still without disturba nce for ~36 hours, cubic white crystal s began to precipitate and many flower -shaped white crystals appeared on the bottom of the bottle standing for another 24 hours. The goodness of fit on F2 was 1.307. Flack parameter = 0.020(8).

Cultivation of Crystalline TPP. 200 mg commercialized TPP was added to a  25 ml round -bottomed flask, subsequently a 6 ml mixture of CH 2Cl2 and EtOH (5/1, by volume) was added to dissolve it completely. After standing still without disturba nce for ~36 hours,  block y colorless  crystals appeared in the bottom . Lumpy solid was collect ed after standing for another 24 hours .

HRMS  spectra were recorded on a Q -TOF instrument by electrospray ionization (ESI) technique . X-ray single crystal diffraction data  for the Phos-cage  in DCM/EtOH mixture  was collected on a Bruker Apex diffractometer and 1.5 kW graphite monochromated Mo radiatio n (Öñ = 0.71073 ?) using 0.3 ¡«Àß scan steps spanning at least a hemisphere of reciprocal space for all structures. The frames were integrated with the SAINT v6.45a (Bruker, 2005). A semi -empirical absorption correction using multiple -reflections was carried out using the program SADABS V2008 -1.5X.  The excitation and emission spectra were recorded with a HORIBA Scientific made Fluoromax -4 spectrometer  for samples in solution and at aggregate. The resulting mixture was heated  to reflux for 48 h. After completion of the reaction, solvent was removed .
